        difficulty: 1,
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        content: "<h3>Mean (Average)</h3><p>The <strong>mean</strong> is what most people call the \"average.\" To find it:</p><div class=\"lesson-formula\">Mean $= \\frac{\\text{Sum of all values}}{\\text{Number of values}}$</div><p>This formula works in both directions. If you know the mean and the count, you can find the sum: Sum $=$ Mean $\\times$ Count. The SAT loves to test this reverse direction.</p><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 1</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> The average of 5 test scores is 82. If four of the scores are 78, 85, 90, and 76, what is the fifth score?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: Total of all 5 scores = Mean $\\times$ Count = $82 \\times 5 = 410$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: Sum of the four known scores: $78 + 85 + 90 + 76 = 329$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 3: Fifth score = $410 - 329 = 81$</div></div></div><h3>Median</h3><p>The <strong>median</strong> is the middle value when all numbers are arranged in order from least to greatest.</p><ul><li>If there is an <strong>odd</strong> number of values, the median is the single middle number.</li><li>If there is an <strong>even</strong> number of values, the median is the average of the two middle numbers.</li></ul><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 2</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> Find the median of: $12, 7, 3, 15, 9, 21, 5$</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: Arrange in order: $3, 5, 7, 9, 12, 15, 21$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: There are 7 values (odd), so the median is the 4th value: $9$</div></div></div><h3>Mode and Range</h3><ul><li><strong>Mode:</strong> The value that appears most often. A data set can have no mode, one mode, or multiple modes.</li><li><strong>Range:</strong> The difference between the largest and smallest values. Range $=$ Max $-$ Min.</li></ul><h3>How Changes Affect Mean and Median</h3><p>The SAT frequently asks what happens when you add or remove a data point:</p><ul><li>Adding a value <strong>above the mean</strong> raises the mean. Adding a value below the mean lowers it.</li><li>The median is <strong>resistant to outliers</strong> &mdash; extreme values do not affect it much.</li><li>The mean is <strong>sensitive to outliers</strong> &mdash; one extreme value can pull it up or down significantly.</li></ul><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 3</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> The set $\\{10, 12, 14, 15, 19\\}$ has a mean of 14. If the value 50 is added to the set, what happens to the mean and median?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">New mean = $\\frac{10 + 12 + 14 + 15 + 19 + 50}{6} = \\frac{120}{6} = 20$. The mean increased from 14 to 20 (pulled up by the outlier).</div><div class=\"step\">New median: sorted set is $\\{10, 12, 14, 15, 19, 50\\}$. Middle two values are 14 and 15, so median $= \\frac{14+15}{2} = 14.5$.</div><div class=\"step\">Old median was 14. It barely changed, showing the median resists outliers.</div></div></div><h3>Reading Graphs and Tables</h3><p>The SAT will show you bar graphs, line graphs, scatterplots, and tables. The key skills are:</p><ul><li>Read axis labels carefully &mdash; know what each axis represents and what the units are</li><li>Identify trends (increasing, decreasing, no trend)</li><li>Find specific values by reading coordinates carefully</li><li>Compare categories in bar graphs</li></ul><h3>Two-Way Frequency Tables</h3><p>A two-way table organizes data by two categories. You will be asked to find totals, probabilities, or percentages from these tables.</p><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 4</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> A survey of 200 students asked about their favorite sport. The results:</p><p>Boys who prefer Basketball: 45, Boys who prefer Soccer: 35. Girls who prefer Basketball: 40, Girls who prefer Soccer: 80.</p><p>What fraction of soccer fans are boys?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: Total soccer fans = $35 + 80 = 115$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: Boys who prefer soccer = $35$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 3: Fraction = $\\frac{35}{115} = \\frac{7}{23}$</div></div></div><div class=\"lesson-key-point\"><strong>SAT Tip:</strong> When a question says \"what fraction of [group A] chose [option B],\" the denominator is the total of group A, not the total of everything. Read carefully to see which group they are asking about.</div><div class=\"lesson-key-point\"><strong>Common Trap:</strong> Do not confuse mean and median! If a question asks for the median of a large data set given in a frequency table, you need to count to the middle position &mdash; do not just average the numbers you see in the table.</div>",
        keyFormulas: [
            "Mean $= \\frac{\\text{Sum of all values}}{\\text{Number of values}}$",
            "Sum $=$ Mean $\\times$ Count (reverse formula)",
            "Median: middle value when data is sorted",
            "Range $=$ Maximum $-$ Minimum",
            "Mean is sensitive to outliers; median is resistant to outliers"
        ],
        questionIds: ["ps-stat-001", "ps-stat-002", "ps-stat-003", "ps-stat-004", "ps-stat-005"]
