        content: "<h3>Basic Probability</h3><p><strong>Probability</strong> measures how likely something is to happen, on a scale from 0 (impossible) to 1 (certain). The fundamental formula is:</p><div class=\"lesson-formula\">$P(\\text{event}) = \\frac{\\text{Number of favorable outcomes}}{\\text{Total number of outcomes}}$</div><p>For example, if a bag has 3 red marbles and 7 blue marbles (10 total), the probability of drawing a red marble is $\\frac{3}{10} = 0.3$ or $30\\%$.</p><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 1</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> A standard deck of cards has 52 cards (4 suits with 13 cards each). What is the probability of drawing a heart?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">There are 13 hearts out of 52 total cards.</div><div class=\"step\">$P(\\text{heart}) = \\frac{13}{52} = \\frac{1}{4} = 0.25$</div></div></div><h3>Probability from Two-Way Tables</h3><p>The SAT often shows a two-way frequency table and asks you to find a probability. The key is to identify the correct \"group\" (row, column, or total) to use as your denominator.</p><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 2</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> In a survey, 120 students were asked if they prefer cats or dogs. Of the 50 boys, 20 prefer cats and 30 prefer dogs. Of the 70 girls, 45 prefer cats and 25 prefer dogs. If a girl is selected at random, what is the probability she prefers dogs?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: We are told \"a girl is selected,\" so our group is all girls = 70.</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: Girls who prefer dogs = 25.</div><div class=\"step\">Step 3: $P(\\text{dogs} | \\text{girl}) = \\frac{25}{70} = \\frac{5}{14}$</div></div></div><h3>Exponential Growth and Decay</h3><p>While linear functions grow by a constant amount (adding the same number each time), <strong>exponential functions</strong> grow by a constant multiplier (multiplying by the same number each time).</p><div class=\"lesson-formula\">Exponential growth: $y = a(1 + r)^t$</div><div class=\"lesson-formula\">Exponential decay: $y = a(1 - r)^t$</div><p>Where:</p><ul><li>$a$ = the initial amount (starting value)</li><li>$r$ = the rate of growth or decay (as a decimal)</li><li>$t$ = time</li></ul><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 3</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> A population of bacteria doubles every 3 hours. If there are initially 500 bacteria, which function models the population $P$ after $t$ hours?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: The initial amount $a = 500$.</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: The population doubles (multiplied by 2) every 3 hours.</div><div class=\"step\">Step 3: $P(t) = 500 \\cdot 2^{t/3}$</div><div class=\"step\">We use $t/3$ as the exponent because doubling happens every 3 hours, not every 1 hour.</div></div></div><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 4</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> A car purchased for $\\$20{,}000$ depreciates at $15\\%$ per year. What is it worth after 4 years?</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">This is exponential decay with $a = 20000$, $r = 0.15$, $t = 4$.</div><div class=\"step\">$V = 20000(1 - 0.15)^4 = 20000(0.85)^4$</div><div class=\"step\">$(0.85)^4 = 0.52200625$</div><div class=\"step\">$V = 20000 \\times 0.522 \\approx \\$10{,}440.13$</div></div></div><h3>Basic Trigonometry (SOH CAH TOA)</h3><p>Trigonometry relates the angles and sides of right triangles. There are three main ratios:</p><div class=\"lesson-formula\">$\\sin(\\theta) = \\frac{\\text{Opposite}}{\\text{Hypotenuse}}$ (SOH)</div><div class=\"lesson-formula\">$\\cos(\\theta) = \\frac{\\text{Adjacent}}{\\text{Hypotenuse}}$ (CAH)</div><div class=\"lesson-formula\">$\\tan(\\theta) = \\frac{\\text{Opposite}}{\\text{Adjacent}}$ (TOA)</div><p>\"Opposite\" means the side across from the angle you are looking at. \"Adjacent\" means the side next to the angle (that is not the hypotenuse). The <strong>hypotenuse</strong> is always the longest side, opposite the right angle.</p><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 5</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> In a right triangle, the side opposite angle $A$ is 5 and the hypotenuse is 13. Find $\\sin(A)$, $\\cos(A)$, and $\\tan(A)$.</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Step 1: Find the adjacent side using the Pythagorean theorem: $a^2 + 5^2 = 13^2$, so $a^2 = 169 - 25 = 144$, so $a = 12$.</div><div class=\"step\">Step 2: $\\sin(A) = \\frac{\\text{Opposite}}{\\text{Hypotenuse}} = \\frac{5}{13}$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 3: $\\cos(A) = \\frac{\\text{Adjacent}}{\\text{Hypotenuse}} = \\frac{12}{13}$</div><div class=\"step\">Step 4: $\\tan(A) = \\frac{\\text{Opposite}}{\\text{Adjacent}} = \\frac{5}{12}$</div></div></div><p>A key identity the SAT tests: $\\sin(x) = \\cos(90째 - x)$. This means the sine of an angle equals the cosine of its complement.</p><h3>Absolute Value Equations</h3><p>The <strong>absolute value</strong> of a number is its distance from zero on the number line. It is always positive (or zero).</p><div class=\"lesson-formula\">$|x| = x$ if $x \\geq 0$, and $|x| = -x$ if $x < 0$</div><p>To solve an absolute value equation like $|ax + b| = c$:</p><ul><li>Set up two equations: $ax + b = c$ AND $ax + b = -c$</li><li>Solve both equations</li><li>Check both solutions in the original equation</li></ul><div class=\"lesson-example\"><div class=\"lesson-example-label\">Example 6</div><p><strong>Problem:</strong> Solve $|2x - 3| = 7$</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><div class=\"explanation-text\"><div class=\"step\">Case 1: $2x - 3 = 7$, so $2x = 10$, so $x = 5$</div><div class=\"step\">Case 2: $2x - 3 = -7$, so $2x = -4$, so $x = -2$</div><div class=\"step\">Check: $|2(5) - 3| = |7| = 7$ &#10003; and $|2(-2) - 3| = |-7| = 7$ &#10003;</div><div class=\"step\">Both solutions are valid: $x = 5$ or $x = -2$</div></div></div><div class=\"lesson-key-point\"><strong>SAT Tip:</strong> For exponential growth/decay questions, the SAT often provides the equation and asks you to interpret what the numbers mean. The base (the number being raised to a power) tells you the growth or decay factor. If it is greater than 1, it is growth. If it is between 0 and 1, it is decay.</div><div class=\"lesson-key-point\"><strong>Common Trap:</strong> When solving absolute value equations, remember that $|x| = -5$ has NO solution, because absolute value cannot be negative. Also, always check your solutions, because some may be extraneous.</div>",
